Crawford County Career and Technical Center
Yesterday at 8:03 AM ·

BOOKKEEPER

Crawford County Career and Technical Center has a full-time opening for a Bookkeeper starting on or about October 22, 2020. Qualifications are an Associate Degree preferred, working knowledge of basic accounting principles and practices, current Act 34, 151 and 114 clearances. Two years’ experience preferred as an accounting clerk in public education or the public sector. Must possess computer, accounting, communication, and general business knowledge. Individual must be qualified to assume the position as a bonded agent. Salary as per negotiated contract. Applications may be obtained at CCCTC.

Send application, resume, three (3) letters of reference, and clearances to: Mr. Kevin Sprong, Director, Crawford County CTC, 860 Thurston Road, Meadville, PA 16335.

Deadline is September 30, 2020. EOE

post_text:
RELEASED TIME UPDATE

Despite the COVID-19 challenges of this year, Released Time “classes” will continue, online.

Go to Meadville Youth Vision on Facebook to find out more.

Meadville Youth Vision has offered the RT Program at Crawford Central Schools since 2005. According to PA Public School Code section 1546, and 1982 amendment Act 175, students who are interested, with parent permission, are legally allowed to be “released” from school for 1 hour a week for religious education.

Since releasing students from school campus during the day is prohibitive right now, MYV will make “classes” available online. Age-appropriate recorded video messages by some RT teachers can be accessed on Meadville Youth Vision’s Facebook page. Our content will remain the same as before - exposure to the Bible and Who Jesus is.

Messages will begin the first Wednesday in October, and each Wednesday a new lesson will be posted on the MYV FB page. You can go to them at any time.

Meadville Middle School Football

Please refer to the MeadvilleAthletics.org site for all current updates and schedules. Announcements will also be made on the MASH AD Facebook and Twitter accounts.

7th and 8th grade uniforms and equipment will be handed out on Saturday August 8th, from 8am to 11am. Each student's time slot must be scheduled ahead of time.

Sports Physicals must be completed before practice on Monday August 10th. The official PIAA Physical form must be used and can be downloaded from the MeadvilleAthletics.org site or picked up at MASH.

Please contact Coach Radnich at robert.radnich@craw.org for further information and to let the coaches know of your child's interest.
text:
Meadville Middle School Football

Please refer to the MeadvilleAthletics.org site for all current updates and schedules. Announcements will also be made on the MASH AD Facebook and Twitter accounts.

7th and 8th grade uniforms and equipment will be handed out on Saturday August 8th, from 8am to 11am. Each student's time slot must be scheduled ahead of time.

Meadville Area Senior High School
May 13 at 3:12 PM ·

Announcement for seniors:

Caps and gowns may be picked up at MASH on Sunday, May 17 from 2-4 and Monday, May 18 from 10-12. This will follow a curbside delivery format, where vehicles will pull up in front of the school, student/parents will provide us with the graduate's name, and their cap/gown/cords will be delivered to the car. Students or parents that walk to the school may line up under the canopy on the sidewalk and are asked to follow social distancing protocols.

Caps and gowns may be picked up early so that they can be hung up and/or steamed prior to the virtual graduation ceremony. Students should come dressed in their cap and gown during their designated time slot. Diplomas will be handed out during the videotaping session, so please make sure to spread the word!

This was the message of the all-call for Cochranton Jr.-Sr. High students that went out Friday night.

Students will be permitted into Cochranton Jr/Sr High School on May 14th and 15th between the times of 9:00 a.m. - 11:30 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. - 3:00 p.m. to clean out their lockers and gym lockers. Library books and uniforms should be returned along with any other school business at that time. Laptops and curriculum books will be returned after June 5th. Masks should be worn and social distancing protocols will be followed. If you are unable to make these dates, contact one of the Principals to arrange an alternative time. If you have any other questions or concerns, please contact Mr. Wigton and Mr. McCurdy directly through the phone answering system or their emails. Thank you and stay safe.

post_text:
On the second day of our school closure, twelve MASH German students were scheduled to attend the American Association of Teachers of German’s Three Rivers German Day at Washington and Jefferson College. Each student planned a submission for various competitions including art, poetry recitation, writing, and/or a dramatic presentation, all in German. Our Bulldogs competed against students from all over western PA and West Virginia. Because of the cancellation, students submitted photographed or recorded entries.
Congratulations to the MASH students who earned certificates and prizes:
Laura Barnes – 1st place, handicraft
Anna Minor – 2nd place, painting
Mariah Mauser – 3rd place, painting
Krysta Germanoski – 3rd place, handicraft

post_text: Congratulations to Meadville Area Senior High School's Junior Trombonist, Adam Duffy, for qualifying to be a member of the Pennsylvania Music Educators Associations All-State Orchestra!! The PMEA All-State Festival was to happen this week at the Kalahari Resort in the Poconos. Unfortunately, that event had to be cancelled due to COVID-19. However, we want to honor the success of our students and extend a ‘Thank You’ to PMEA for allowing our students to submit auditions online so they could continue with the advancement process.

Allegheny Students for Environmental Action
April 20 at 9:02 AM ·

Happy Earth Week 2020, Crunchies! This year is the 50th Earth Day! ❤️🌏 In addition, Allegheny College has officially reached its goal of Carbon Neutrality! Thank you so much for all your hard work, Allegheny College Sustainability!

Although we couldn't celebrate together in person, we collaborated with ECO People at Meadville Area Senior High and the PA Green New Deal Coalition to organize this campaign, #QuaranCleanUp! Clean up your room, home, lawn, street, or neighborhood (whichever needs it and whichever you can access safely), fill out this Bingo Board, and share it with us using the hashtag #QuaranCleanUp. Then, challenge 5 (or more) friends to do the same. 💪😎 ALSO! Check out our friends at Green Shoppe PA; Julie is offering a special prize for anyone that successfully scores a bingo! Thank you so much, Julie. ❤️❤️❤️

This campaign starts TODAY and will be celebrated/summarized on the last day of Earth Week, this Sunday, April 26 -- but it can keep going after that. ✌️😉 Hope to see you all posting!

Love, the SEA Board 💚

Lincoln Recycling - Meadville
April 14 at 2:52 PM ·

This time of year we typically have a coloring contest for kids in grades K-5 in Millcreek as well as Crawford Central and the winners get a pizza party for their class. Since school is cancelled we are going to open this up to ALL kids grades K-5 in Erie and Crawford County!

All drawings can be emailed to Andrew Lincoln at alincoln@lincolnrecycling.com, and we will post the Top 20 drawings. Then we'll leave it to Facebook to vote for their favorite drawing by the number of "likes" each drawing gets.

The top 3 will get a pizza party for their family and the winner will also get to choose a hospital listed below to have a lunch donated by Lincoln Recycling to support the healthcare workers during COVID-19.

Hospitials: UPMC Hamot, AHN Sain Vincent, Meadville Medical Center

IMPORTANT DATES: drawings are due by Saturday, April 18th. Voting will take place April 20-22nd. The winners will be announced on Earth Day, Wednesday April 22nd!

post_text:
A message from Mrs. Tamara Clark, Principal at West End Elementary School

Hello everyone!

We miss seeing your smiling faces on a daily basis and it was so nice to see those who came to get their instructional packets! It was a time to share a smile during these trying times...I was hoping to get to every car, however for efficiency reasons, I missed a few. This leads me to wanting to thank Mrs. Lockwood and Mrs. Redden for making our pick up time very smooth. Given that we were handing out instructional packets, fundraising chocolates and instruments all at the same time, we couldn't have asked for better results! Thank you to all the families for their patience while in line!

Stay tuned for our next step regarding instruction!
Tamara Clark, WE Principal

Meadville Area Senior High School
March 27 at 7:02 PM ·

UPDATE: Several kind people have asked how they can donate food to the Caring Cupboard. We will offer a no-contact, drive-by, drop-off from 2-4 pm on Wednesday, April 1. Carts will be located outside in front of the MASH main entrance. You may leave non-perishable items on the cart. Thank you!

The MASH Caring Cupboard provides 26 weekend food bags to our students in need. Each bag costs $5-$6 to prepare which includes breakfast, lunch, dinner, and snack options, as well as toiletries, if available.

When the bags were packed this morning, it became very apparent that the Caring Cupboard will only be able to provide this service for approximately 2-3 more weeks unless it collects donations to sustain this much needed service to the students. We are aware that many community agencies and families are financially strapped right now, but if you feel compelled to donate, please mail a check to The MASH Caring Cupboard, Meadville Area Senior High School, 930 North Street, Meadville, PA 16335.

post_text:
Attention AP Students

Collegeboard has just announced that they will not be giving any face to face AP exams this school year. instead students will take a 45 minute free-response at home exam. For each AP exam 2 dates will be provided 1 early (for students who want the advantage of having the information fresh) and 1 late exam (to allow for students who want to take more time to study)

The dates for each AP exam will be released on April 3rd.
The tests can be accessed from a number of devices and the AP will be providing support services for anyone with difficulty accessing the tests.

Beginning March 25th relevant free-response questions in AP classroom will be released so that students can access practice questions. AP classroom will have lessons posted as well

Everything described above is also sent to each students email (the one you used to register for the AP exams)

For more information go to your email or to collegeboard.org or you can access the lessons and free-response questions at youtube.com/advancedplacement

post_text:
The Department of Education (PDE) announced all schools in the Commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6th as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6th if necessary, to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

Under the new timeline, school buildings would reopen on April 7 for two days to allow school administrators, teachers and other staff time to prepare classrooms, set up cafeterias, schedule transportation and arrange other business operations. Students would return to school on April 9th, unless extending the closure is needed in response to the situation with the virus at that time.

If schools are reopened, the Department of Education has not provided direction on how districts are to handle the current number of school days required. Therefore, it is premature at this point to predict how we will handle Easter break.

Directions for continuing education will be coming shortly.

PMEA Chorus Fest was held at MASH on Thursday, March 5th. It was co-hosted by Stephanie Chocchi at First District Elementary and Molly Moyer at Meadville Area High School.
140 students from Crawford, Erie and Warren Counties arrived at Meadville Area High School early in the morning and rehearsed with guest conductor, Richard Freysinger from Conneaut School District. They performed a concert at the MASH auditorium that evening.

Directors were able to attend an Act 48 Clinic during the day on Little Kids Rock. This was presented by Dr. Craig Denison from Indiana University of PA Music Department.

Music Directors participating from Crawford Central were:
First District Elementary – Stephanie Chiocchi
Cochranton Elementary – Leslie Jensen
Second District Elementary – Traci Balsamo
West End Elementary – Leslie Jensen and Rachel Miller

Congratulations to these students and Directors on a fine concert last night and happy Music In Our Schools Month!

post_text: One aspect of Meadville, The Beloved Community Fair, held at Meadville Area Middle School on February 19th, invited students to present projects they had made about Meadville. The students of Mrs. Herbstritt's English class prepared Preposition Riddles for locations around Meadville. They all chose a different location and created 6 different prepositional phrases to describe the surroundings of the "mystery" location. Two of the students stayed after school to present to their peers, other adults, and judges. At the end of the event, Mrs. Herbstritt's class' Preposition Riddles were voted as 1st place winners in the Group Presentation category! Congratulations!!

post_text: Congratulations to Anthony Del Rio, Larin Douglas, Damuree Gavin, Caden Ream, Kirstin Ream, and Ty Tidball for winning the 2nd Quarter Teen Wellness Cookie Bake-Off contest at MAMS with their Penny Cookie. Students had to work with their assigned cooking group to find a recipe that met the guidelines of the contest and approval of the teacher. The Penny Cookie was a modified version of a chocolate chip cookie by adding Oreo crumbs instead of chocolate chips to the dough. Then, the group wanted the cookie to have a creative appearance so they melted the chocolate chips and drizzled the chocolate on top of the cookie. Several faculty and staff volunteered to judge the event and used a student-created score card to place the eleven cookies that were entered. In addition to the faculty and staff judges, five students had the opportunity to judge through the Paws for Pride Rewards program. Congratulations to the winners and thanks to all the students, faculty, and staff who participated. (Not pictured: Anthony Del Rio)
text: Congratulations to Anthony Del Rio, Larin Douglas, Damuree Gavin, Caden Ream, Kirstin Ream, and Ty Tidball for winning the 2nd Quarter Teen Wellness Cookie Bake-Off contest at MAMS with their Penny Cookie. post_text: The Meadville Lions Club recently announced the local contest winners for the 2020 Lions International Peace Poster Contest. The theme for this year’s project was “Journey of Peace.” Twenty-four international Peace Poster entries are selected each year, representing the work of approximately 400,000 young participants worldwide. Crawford Central School District’s “Journey of Peace” poster winners are Sophiah Carletti-Turner - First District Elementary School (Kari Unice- teacher) and Chandler Ploski - Cochranton Jr. Sr. High School (Janice Steck- teacher). Students and their teachers are pictured with King Lion CIndy Fiorillo. Each student received a cash prize and a certificate of appreciation from the Lions Club. Congratulations Sophiah and Chandler!

Many thanks to the families who joined us this morning at the Be A Buddy Not A Bully Workshop. This event was co-sponsored by the Title I and Special Education programs. We’d like to extend our thanks to Audrey Smith MA, Licensed Psychologist, & Harry Nelson, MA, from Parkside Psychological for the very information Keynote. Thanks to LTI for providing childcare. We appreciate the involvement of Women’s Services and the Crawford County Drug and Alcohol Executive Commission. And, of course, we need to recognize the efforts of the Title I Reading Specialists, Special Education teachers, and Guidance Counselors for their work to help make the event a success.

Here are a few of the resources that were shared today:
https://www.pacer.org/bullying/
https://www.stopbullying.gov
http://www.thebullyproject.com

Let’s be Upstanders rather than Bystanders! (From https://www.stopbullying.gov/prevention/bystanders-to-bullying/index.html)

post_text: This past Friday evening, an all-call went out to remind parents that there was no school for students today. The delivery results we received from that call indicate that 20% of the phone numbers in our system where not successfully reached. If you did not receive a call, please contact your child's school to make sure we have your correct number. There are other reasons a call might not go through such as you have changed cell phone carriers since last year, you do not have your voicemail set up or have an answering machine, etc. We are here to help resolve the issue. Thank you.

post_text: Just a reminder of tomorrow night’s Title I Literacy Under the Lights event! Join us on Bender Field from 6:00 p.m. - 7:30 p.m. to celebrate reading/literacy in our community! Bring a blanket for the Halftime Huddle where everyone will read on the field for 15 minutes. Several local agencies will be on the field as well as Waldo!! The United Way of Western Crawford County will be there to register families with preschoolers (age 5 and under) living in the 16335 zip code to receive a free book in the mail every month through the Dolly Parton Imagination Library. You will need proof of residency (driver’s license will work!). Join in the Scavenger Hunt. Participate in the Book Swap. Listen to Guest Readers. Everyone is welcome. Hope to see you there!

shared_text:
Crawford County Career and Technical Center
October 3, 2019 at 9:26 AM ·

Attention All Crawford County High School Seniors and Parents/Guardians

The Community College of Allegheny County (CCAC) is going to be offering two FREE college course programs at the Crawford County CTC. This is a great opportunity for Crawford County senior students who may not have enrolled at the Tech Center, or Tech Center students who want to expand their career choices in their field or another one, or students going to a post secondary school where these credits are in line with what their major will be. Senior students can earn 27 credits in Welding Technology or 23 college credits in Machine Technician. Again these are FREE classes to Crawford County Seniors! Classes would be held from 3:30-8:30 Monday through Thursday’s, at the tech center from the end of October until the beginning or middle of May. That’s right, that number of credits in approximately 6 months.. not even an entire school year! Applications close on Monday and can be turned in at the CCCTC. Email lhummer@keystonecec.org or jottney@gmail.com with questions!

post_text: The Second District Title I Teachers hosted an Award Winning Book Celebration at Open House on September 26, 2019. Featured books were from three book medal categories: Caldecott, Newbery, and Coretta Scott King. Each child that visited, looked through ten books and then had a chance to win their favorite book. Winners were recognized during morning announcements.
